
Magnolia is an Open-Source content management system (CMS) developed by Magnolia International Ltd., based in Basel, Switzerland. It is based on JSR-170.

==History==

Magnolia 1.0 was released November 15, 2003 by Obinary Ltd.[tpl]cite news | first= | last= | coauthors= |authorlink= | title=Obinary Releases Free Java-based Enterprise CMS | date=2003-11-20 | publisher=Simpler Media Group | url =http://www.cmswire.com/cms/open-source-cms/obinary-releases-free-javabased-enterprise-cms-000086.php | work =CMSWire | pages = | accessdate = 2009-01-25 | language = [/tpl] Magnolia 2.0 was released November 15, 2004 [tpl]cite news | first=Brice | last=Dunwoodie | coauthors= |authorlink= | title=Magnolia 2.0 Released, J2EE Open-Source CMS | date=2004-11-16 | publisher=Simpler Media Group | url =http://www.cmswire.com/cms/open-source-cms/magnolia-20-released-j2ee-opensource-cms-000475.php | work =CMSWire | pages = | accessdate = 2009-01-25 | language = [/tpl] with a focus on usability.
Obinary was renamed to Magnolia International Ltd. in September 2006. By that time, Magnolia had been downloaded more than 150,000 times.[tpl]cite news | first=Boris | last=Kraft | coauthors= |authorlink= | title=Obinary, Creator of Leading Enterprise Content Management System "Magnolia", Renamed to Magnolia International Ltd. | date=2006-09-19 | publisher=Vocus PRW Holdings, LLC | url =http://www.prweb.com/releases/2006/09/prweb439195.htm | work =PRWeb | pages = | accessdate = 2009-01-25 | language = [/tpl][tpl]Self-published inline|date=April 2010[/tpl]
Magnolia 3.0, released on November 15, 2006, marked the switch from a pure Open Source product to a layered product strategy with the introduction of Magnolia Enterprise Edition. The proprietary version extends the open source version by adding user authentication through LDAP, a package manager to manage deployments, a JSR-168 connector and a WYSIWYG website designer[tpl]cite news | first=Angela | last=Natividad | coauthors= |authorlink= | title=Magnolia Turns 3, Updates Web CMS | date=2006-11-15 | publisher=Simpler Media Group | url =http://www.cmswire.com/cms/open-source-cms/magnolia-turns-3-updates-web-cms-000901.php | work =CMSWire | pages = | accessdate = 2009-01-25 | language = [/tpl]
Magnolia 3.6 was released in July 2008 and focused on the ease of maintenance, robustness and performance.[tpl]cite news | first=Boris | last=Kraft | coauthors= |authorlink= | title=Magnolia Version 3.6 Ten Times Faster; Includes New Enterprise Features | date=2008-07-30 | publisher=Magnolia International Ltd. | url =http://www.magnolia-cms.com/home/news/press-releases/magnolia-3-6-released.html | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2009-01-25 | language = [/tpl] [tpl]Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot[/tpl]
In December 2008, Magnolia released "Magnolia-on-Air", a content management system designed for broadcasters and large organizations to manage their broadcast content.[tpl]cite news | first=Eileen | last=Mullan | coauthors= |authorlink= | title=Helping Broadcasters Bloom with Magnolia: a CMS for the Broadcasting Media | date=2008-12-09 | publisher=Information Today Inc. | url =http://www.econtentmag.com/Articles/News/News-Feature/Helping-Broadcasters-Bloom-with-Magnolia-a-CMS-for-the-Broadcasting-Media-51844.htm | work =EContent | pages = | accessdate = 2009-01-25 | language = [/tpl]
In March 2009, Magnolia released Magnolia 4.0.[tpl]cite web|url=http://www.theserverside.com/news/thread.tss?thread_id=53948 |title=Open Source CMS Magnolia 4.0 Released |accessdate=2009-03-24 |last=Initmarketing Staff |date=2009-03-12 |work=The Server Side [/tpl]
Magnolia 4.1 was released in June 2009. It introduces user-generated content templates that provide new functionality, including forums and public user registration. It also includes new features like a CMS-wide address book, multiple themes, RSS generation and aggregation.[tpl]cite web|url=http://www.magnolia-cms.com/4-1 |title=Open Source CMS Magnolia 4.1 Released |accessdate=2009-03-24 |last=Initmarketing Staff |date=2009-06-25 |work=Magnolia Ltd [/tpl]
Magnolia 4.4 was released in November 2010. It introduced support for concurrent editing and the ability to import and export content in different languages. It also included new workflow and dependency controls.[tpl]cite web|url=http://www.fiercecontentmanagement.com/story/magnolia-44-focuses-authors/2010-12-01 |title=Magnolia 4.4 focuses on authors |accessdate=2012-02-17 |last=Miller |first=Ron|date=2010-12-01 |work=Fierce Content Management [/tpl] 
Magnolia 4.5 was released in March 2012. It introduced support for mobile websites and mobile content previews and interoperability with Microsoft Sharepoint, Alfresco, Photoshop, SAP, Oracle and others. It also added support for new enterprise standards like CMIS, JCR 2.0, HTML5 and Java 6.0.[tpl]cite web|url=http://www.cmscritic.com/magnolia-cms-4-5-delivers-instant-mobile-sites-and-multichannel-publishing-with-largest-upgrade-to-date/ |title=Magnolia CMS 4.5 delivers Instant Mobile Sites and Multichannel Publishing with largest upgrade to date |accessdate=2012-03-18 |last=Johnston |first=Mike|date=2012-03-12 |work=CMS Critic [/tpl][tpl]cite web|url=http://www.cmswire.com/cms/web-cms/magnolia-v45-extends-mobile-capabilities-014860.php |title=Magnolia v4.5 Extends Mobile Capabilities |accessdate=2012-03-18 |last=Sechrist |first=Steve|date=2012-03-14 |work=CMS Wire [/tpl]

==Coverage and Reviews==

Since mid 2007,[tpl]cite web|url=http://www.cmswatch.com/Trends/970-Magnolia's-new-enterprise-edition-is-more-of-a-departmental-tool |title=Magnolia's new enterprise edition is more of a departmental tool |accessdate=2009-01-25 |last=Boye |first=Janus |date=2007-07-14 |work=TRENDWATCH BLOG |publisher=CMS Watch [/tpl] Magnolia has been covered by the independent CMS Watch report.[tpl]cite web|url=http://www.cmswatch.com/CMS/Report/ |title=THE WEB CMS REPORT 2009 |accessdate=2009-01-25 |work=CMS Watch |publisher=CMS Watch [/tpl]
It is covered in the "Open Source Content Management in Java" report of Seth Gottlieb, Content Here [tpl]cite web|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/84140831/Open-Source-Web-Content-Management-in-Magnolia |title=Open Source Content Management in Java |accessdate=2009-01-25 |last=Gottlieb |first=Seth |publisher=Content Here [/tpl]
In August 2009, Gartner included Magnolia into their "Magic Quadrant for Web Content Management" report.[tpl]cite web|url=http://mediaproducts.gartner.com/reprints/oracle/article91/article91.html |title= Magic Quadrant for Web Content Management |accessdate=2009-09-14 |last=Mick MacComascaigh, Toby Bell, Mark R. Gilbert |date=2009-96-14 |work=Gartner[/tpl]

==Modules==

Modules offer Spring Framework and Struts integration, RSS feed support, standard templates, data caching and backup, and more. As of February 2012, the Magnolia website lists over 50 free modules.[tpl]cite web|url=http://store.magnolia-cms.com/module-list.html |title= Module store server |accessdate=2012-02-21 |work=Magnolia CMS Website[/tpl]

==Users==

Magnolia CMS users include the US Navy,[tpl]cite web|url=http://cmsreport.com/blog/2010/magnolia-cms-and-us-navy |title= The Magnolia CMS and the U.S. Navy |accessdate=2011-08-31 |last=Ruby |first=Bryan |date=2010-11-11 |work=CMS Report[/tpl] Scottish Widows[tpl]cite web|url=http://www.computing.co.uk/ctg/news/2121697/-source-cms-underpins-scottish-widows-financial-planning-web-site |title=Open-source CMS underpins Scottish Widows financial planning web site |accessdate=2012-02-21 |work=Computing |last=Shah| first=Sooraj| publisher=Incisive Media|date=2011-11-02[/tpl][tpl]cite web|url=http://www.fstech.co.uk/fst/Magnolia_CMS_Scottish_Widows.php |title=CSC/Scottish Widows choose Magnolia CMS |accessdate=2012-02-21 |work=Financial Sector Technology |last=Thompson| first=Scott| publisher=Perspective Publishing Limited|date=2011-10-31[/tpl] and Middle East Broadcasting Center (MBC).[tpl]cite web|url=http://www.cmscritic.com/mbc-chooses-magnolia-cms/ |title= MBC Chooses Magnolia CMS  |accessdate=2011-09-03 |work=CMS Critic |last=Johnston| first=Mike| publisher=CMS Critic[/tpl]
The official Magnolia CMS site has a directory of example users: Magnolia CMS References

==Awards==

In September 2010, Magnolia won the Swiss Open Source Award in the Contribution category.[tpl]cite web|url=http://www.ossawards.ch/awards-2010/ |title=CH Open Source Awards 2010 |accessdate=2011-08-11 |work=Swiss Open Systems User Group |publisher=Swiss Open Systems User Group [/tpl][tpl]cite news|url=http://www.cmscritic.com/magnolia-cms-wins-swiss-open-source-award/ |title=Magnolia CMS wins Swiss Open source award |date=2010-09-02 |work=CMS Critic |last=Johnston| first=Mike| publisher=CMS Critic [/tpl]
In May 2011, the Red Herring editorial team selected Magnolia as part of the 2011 Top 100 Europe.[tpl]cite web|url=http://www.herring100.com/RHE/2011/top100.html |title=2011 Red Herring Top 100 Europe |accessdate=2011-08-11 |work=Red Herring |publisher=Red Herring [/tpl]

==Magnolia Conference==

